    add particle background

    I'll add a beautiful particle background system to enhance the visual appeal of the portfolio. Let me create an interactive particle system that responds to mouse movement.

    Version 2

    I've added a sophisticated particle background system with the following features:

    Particle System Features:

    1. Dynamic Particles: 150 floating particles that move organically across the screen
    2. Mouse Interaction: Particles are attracted to mouse movement, creating an interactive experience
    3. Connection Lines: Nearby particles connect with subtle red lines, creating a network effect
    4. Theme Integration: Uses the portfolio's color scheme (red, cyan, white) with proper opacity
    5. Glow Effects: Each particle has a subtle glow effect for enhanced visual appeal
    6. Performance Optimized: Particle count adjusts based on screen size for optimal performance
    7. Lifecycle Management: Particles fade in/out naturally and respawn continuously

    Technical Implementation:

    • Canvas-based: Uses HTML5 Canvas for smooth 60fps animations
    • Responsive: Automatically adjusts to screen size changes
    • Memory Efficient: Proper cleanup and particle recycling
    • Non-intrusive: Positioned behind all content with pointer-events-none
    • Mobile Friendly: Reduced particle count on smaller screens

    Visual Effects:

    • Particles drift slowly with organic movement
    • Mouse proximity creates attraction forces
    • Connecting lines form and break dynamically
    • Subtle color variations match the design theme
    • Smooth fade-in/out transitions

    The particle background adds depth and movement to the portfolio while maintaining excellent performance and not interfering with content readability. The interactive mouse effects create an engaging experience that complements the modern design aesthetic.

    components/about.tsx
    Edited

    I've fixed the JSX syntax error by properly escaping the curly braces. The issue was that JSX was trying to interpret {accuracy:.2f} as JavaScript code instead of displaying it as text. Now it uses {'{'} and {'}'} to render the literal curly braces as text content.
